SIMPLE: gush
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Gush
<hw>Gush</hw> <pr>(g⟦ucr⟧sh)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. &
p. p.</pos> <conjf>Gushed</conjf> <pr>(g⟦ucr⟧sht)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. &
vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Gushing</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OE.
<ets>guschen</ets>, cf. Icel. <ets>gusa</ets> and <ets>gjsa</ets>, also
D. <ets>gucsen</ets>; perh. akin to AS. <ets>ge⟦oacute⟧tan</ets> to
pour, G. <ets>giessen</ets>, Goth. <ets>giutan</ets>, E. <ets>gut</ets>.
Cf. <er>Found</er> to cast.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>To issue with violence and rapidity, as a fluid; to
rush forth as a fluid from confinement; to flow copiously.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He smote the rock that the waters <qex>gushed</qex> out.</q>
<rj><qau>Ps ixxviii 20.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A sea of blood <qex>gushed</qex> from the gaping wound.</q>
<rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To make a sentimental or untimely exhibition of
affection; to display enthusiasm in a silly, demonstrative manner.</def>
<mark>[Colloq.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Gush</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Gush
<hw>Gush</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A sudden and violent
issue of a fluid from an inclosed plase; an emission of a liquid in a
large quantity, and with force; the fluid thus emitted; a rapid
outpouring of anything; <as>as, a <ex>gush</ex> of song from a
bird</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The <qex>gush</qex> of springs,⟦br⟧
An fall of lofty foundains.</q> <rj><qau>Byron.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A sentimental exhibition of affection or enthusiasm,
etc.; effusive display of sentiment.</def> <mark>[Collog.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Gusher</ent>⟦br⟧
